{"questionId":"29448855","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>One of the goats, Brenda, fights with the other goats. The farmer plans to place a second fence with a fixed length of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> metres between the wall and the hedge to form a small triangular field inside <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OAB</mi></math> for Brenda.</p>\n<p>The information is shown on the following diagram.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/70de0d2dff356e6ec50e1b47ba9362f15f9bbe20.png\" width=\"671\" height=\"269\"></p>\n<p>The small triangular field <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OCD</mi></math> has an area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p>\n<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> be the distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OC</mi></math> and let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> be the distance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OD</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>240</mn><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to use the cosine rule in triangle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OCD</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>attempt to use the area formula in triangle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OCD</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)A1</strong></em> for use of the area formula independently of the <em><strong>(M1)A1</strong></em> for use of the cosine rule.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>120</mn><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>240</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>240</mn><mrow><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>28</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>AG</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[5 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"29448855","referenceCode":"24M.2.SL.TZ1.9b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that x2+y2=100+240tan 28°.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 